# =============================================================================
# .dockerignore — files excluded from the Docker build context
#
# The build context is the directory sent to the Docker daemon on `docker build .`
# Excluding unnecessary files:
#   1. Reduces build context transfer time (critical on slow CI connections)
#   2. Prevents stale local build artefacts from shadowing the in-container build
#   3. Ensures secrets and credentials never enter any image layer
#
# The Dockerfile build stages need exactly:
#   pom.xml        — dependency resolution
#   .mvn/          — Maven wrapper configuration
#   mvnw           — Maven wrapper shell script
#   src/           — application source code
#
# Everything else is excluded below.
# =============================================================================

# ── Maven build output ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# target/ is produced by Maven on the developer's machine.
# The Docker build compiles fresh inside the container — local artefacts must
# not be copied in. They may be stale, built for a different JDK, or contain
# test class files that inflate the image size.
target/

# ── Git metadata ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# .git/ contains the full commit history and can be hundreds of MB.
# It is never needed inside the image. Including it would cause every single
# commit to invalidate the entire build context cache.
.git/
.gitignore
.gitattributes

# ── Secrets and environment files ─────────────────────────────────────────────
# CRITICAL: .env contains plaintext credentials. If included in the build
# context, a `COPY . .` directive would bake credentials into an image layer.
# Deleting the file in a subsequent RUN layer does NOT remove it — the layer
# still contains the file in the union filesystem.
.env
*.env
!.env.example

# ── Docker infrastructure files ───────────────────────────────────────────────
# Compose files and the Dockerfile itself are used to BUILD the image,
# not to run inside it. Compose files can reference secret env var names.
Dockerfile
Dockerfile.*
docker-compose*.yml
.dockerignore
Makefile

# ── IDE and editor project files ──────────────────────────────────────────────
.idea/
*.iml
*.ipr
*.iws
.vscode/
.classpath
.project
.settings/
nbproject/
*.swp
*.swo
*~

# ── OS artefacts ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
.DS_Store
.DS_Store?
._*
.Spotlight-V100
.Trashes
ehthumbs.db
Thumbs.db

# ── Application and test logs ─────────────────────────────────────────────────
*.log
logs/
log/

# ── Maven Surefire / Failsafe test reports ────────────────────────────────────
# Test reports are generated inside the container during CI runs.
# Local test output should never enter the production image.
**/surefire-reports/
**/failsafe-reports/
**/test-output/

# ── Documentation ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
README.md
CHANGELOG.md
CONTRIBUTING.md
LICENSE
docs/
*.md

# ── Temporary and scratch files ───────────────────────────────────────────────
tmp/
temp/
*.tmp
*.bak
*.orig
*.rej